  "text": "In a model-checking approach to the verification of multi-agent systems, a MAS is represented by a finite state transition system. [CITATION_1] A state transition system consists of a set of states and transitions between them. Intuitively, each state of a MAS corresponds to a tuple of states of the agents and of the environment, and each transition corresponds to actions performed by the agents. Each state is labelled with atomic propositions that are true in that state. A standard assumption is that each state in the system has at least one outgoing transition (if a state is a deadlock state in the original MAS, we can model this by adding a transition to itself by some null action and labelling it with a 'deadlock' proposition). Properties of the system to be verified are expressed in an appropriate temporal logic L. The model-checking problem for L is, given a state transition system M (and possibly a state s) and an L formula φ, check whether φ is true in M (at state s).",
